docs.abstract: “Defund the police” and “cancel rent” aren’t reforms, but paths to revolution.
docs.snippet: “Defund the police” and “cancel rent” aren’t reforms, but paths to revolution.
docs.lead_paragraph: The uprisings in response to the killing of George Floyd are far different from anything that has come before. Not just because they may be the largest in our history, or that seven weeks in, people are still in the streets (even if the news media has largely moved on). But also because, for the last few years, organizers have been thinking boldly.

headline.main: The Left Is Remaking the World

docs.abstract: A pink brick wall protected the basilica in NoLIta last month during days of civil unrest, just as it did during riots two centuries ago.
docs.snippet: A pink brick wall protected the basilica in NoLIta last month during days of civil unrest, just as it did during riots two centuries ago.
docs.lead_paragraph: Early last month, amid protests against police violence in the wake of the George Floyd killing, the pink brick wall surrounding the cemetery of the original St. Patrick’s Cathedral in NoLIta was spray-painted with graffiti, while a storm window protecting one of the church’s soaring stained-glass windows was broken.

headline.main: At Old St. Pat’s, a History of Defiance

docs.abstract: This 1992 animated movie about Black children running into trouble at a theme park is meant to be a comedy. But for one viewer, it no longer seems so funny.
docs.snippet: This 1992 animated movie about Black children running into trouble at a theme park is meant to be a comedy. But for one viewer, it no longer seems so funny.
docs.lead_paragraph: “The Boondocks,” “Atlanta,” “black-ish,” “Dear White People,” “Sorry to Bother You” — there are a few shows and movies that have dared to use comedy to address the grim state of Black people in America. But lately, I’ve been thinking about a movie I hadn’t seen in more than 20 years: “Bébé’s Kids.” This animated Black comedy explicitly spoke about police brutality and our broken judicial system years before the first utterance of “Black Lives Matter.”

headline.main: ‘Bébé’s Kids’ Shared a Lesson About Racial Injustice
headline.print_headline: On Second Thought, a Movie Isn’t So Funny

docs.abstract: The retention and recruitment problems that many police departments have experienced in recent years are especially pronounced after four Minneapolis officers were charged with Mr. Floyd’s death.
docs.snippet: The retention and recruitment problems that many police departments have experienced in recent years are especially pronounced after four Minneapolis officers were charged with Mr. Floyd’s death.
docs.lead_paragraph: MINNEAPOLIS — Nearly two months after four of its officers were charged with killing George Floyd, the Minneapolis Police Department is reeling, with police officers leaving the job in large numbers, crime surging and politicians planning a top-to-bottom overhaul of the force.

headline.main: Minneapolis Police Experience Surge of Departures in Aftermath of George Floyd Protests

docs.abstract: A reader believes there’s a “double standard” for cooperation with public safety measures.
docs.snippet: A reader believes there’s a “double standard” for cooperation with public safety measures.
docs.lead_paragraph: I have a question that I hope you won’t take the wrong way. I am 72 years old and have been isolating for months. I take Covid-19 very seriously. But I’ve noticed a double standard about safety measures: People who refuse to wear face masks on principle, as a statement of their personal freedom, are shamed about it (often on the internet). But protesters in the Black Lives Matter movement seem to get a free pass on not wearing them. People get agitated when I bring this up. Am I wrong to?

headline.main: Shoppers Should Wear Masks. Shouldn’t Protesters, Too?

docs.abstract: “They’ll kill me. They’ll kill me,” Mr. Floyd pleaded, according to a body camera transcript in court filings by a former officer who wants the charges against him dismissed.
docs.snippet: “They’ll kill me. They’ll kill me,” Mr. Floyd pleaded, according to a body camera transcript in court filings by a former officer who wants the charges against him dismissed.
docs.lead_paragraph: George Floyd’s dying moments have played on an endless loop, horrifying the world and prompting a spasm of street protests, but newly released evidence reveals an even more desperate scene than previously known in the moments before an officer pressed his knee into Mr. Floyd’s neck.

headline.main: New Transcripts Detail Last Moments for George Floyd
headline.print_headline: ‘They’ll Kill Me,’ Floyd Pleaded, Records Reveal

docs.abstract: Epidemiologists have braced for a surge of coronavirus cases. But it has not come yet.
docs.snippet: Epidemiologists have braced for a surge of coronavirus cases. But it has not come yet.
docs.lead_paragraph: For more than two months, the authorities had been urging New Yorkers to stay indoors and keep their distance from others. But after the police killed George Floyd in Minneapolis, tens of thousands of New Yorkers poured into the streets, day and night, to protest police brutality and racism.

headline.main: Did Floyd Protests Lead to a Virus Surge? Here’s What We Know
headline.print_headline: Despite Mass Floyd Protests, New Infections Remain Down. So Far.

docs.abstract: When items like umbrellas and leaf blowers are subverted into objects of resistance, they become very shareable.
docs.snippet: When items like umbrellas and leaf blowers are subverted into objects of resistance, they become very shareable.
docs.lead_paragraph: A video frame captured in Hong Kong in August 2019 shows a group of pro-democracy protesters, smoke pluming toward them, racing to place an orange traffic cone over a tear-gas canister. A video taken nine months later and 7,000 miles away, at a Black Lives Matter protest in Minneapolis, shows another small group using the same maneuver. Two moments, two continents, two cone placers, their postures nearly identical.

headline.main: Why Protest Tactics Spread Like Memes
headline.print_headline: Different Protests, Same Tools of Resistance

byline.original: By Tracy Ma, Natalie Shutler, Jonah E. Bromwich and Shane O'Neill
